# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: monoclonal-antibodies
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] ADCC is independent of the immune complement system that also lyses targets but does not require any other cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] ADCC requires an effector cell which classically is known to be natural killer (NK) cells that typically interact with immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibodies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] However, macrophages, neutrophils and eosinophils can also mediate ADCC, such as eosinophils killing certain parasitic worms known as helminths via IgE antibodies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] In general, ADCC has typically been described as the immune response to antibody-coated cells leading ultimately to the lysing of the infected or non-host cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] In recent literature, its importance in regards to treatment of cancerous cells and deeper insight into its deceptively complex pathways have been topics of increasing interest to medical researchers.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] The typical ADCC involves activation of NK cells by antibodies in a multi-tiered progression of immune control.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] These receptors recognize and bind to the reciprocal portion of an antibody, such as IgG, which binds to the surface of a pathogen-infected target cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] The most common of these Fc receptors on the surface of an NK cell is CD16 or FcγRIII.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Once the Fc receptor binds to the Fc region of the antibody, the NK cell releases cytotoxic factors that cause the death of the target cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] During replication of a virus, some of the viral proteins are expressed on the cell surface membrane of the infected cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Antibodies can then bind to these viral proteins.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Next, the NK cells which have reciprocal Fcγ receptors will bind to that antibody, inducing the NK cell to release proteins such as perforin and proteases known as granzymes, which cause lysis of the infected cell to hinder the spread of the virus.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Large parasites like helminths are too big to be engulfed and killed by phagocytosis.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] They also have an external structure or integument that is resistant to attack by substances released by neutrophils and macrophages.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] After IgE coat these parasites, the Fc receptor (FcɛRI) of an eosinophil will recognize IgE.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Subsequently, interaction between FcεRI and the Fc portion of helminth-bound IgE signals the eosinophil to degranulate.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Several laboratory methods exist for determining the efficacy of antibodies or effector cells in eliciting ADCC.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Usually, a target cell line expressing a certain surface-exposed antigen is incubated with antibody specific for that antigen.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] After washing, effector cells expressing Fc receptor CD16 are co-incubated with the antibody-labelled target cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Effector cells are typically PBMCs (peripheral blood mononuclear cell), of which a small percentage are NK cells (natural killer cell); less often they are purified NK cells themselves.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Over the course of a few hours a complex forms between the antibody, target cell, and effector cell which leads to lysis of the cell membrane of the target.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] If the target cell was pre-loaded with a label of some sort, that label is released in proportion to the amount of cell lysis.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Cytotoxicity can be quantified by measuring the amount of label in solution compared to the amount of label that remains within healthy, intact cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] The classical method of detecting this is the chromium-51 [51Cr] release assay; the sulfur-35 [35S] release assay is a little used radioisotope-based alternative.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Target cell lysis is determined by measuring the amount of radiolabel released into the cell culture medium by means of a gamma counter or scintillation counter.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] A variety of non-radioactive methods are now in widespread use.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Fluorescence-based methods include such things as direct labelling with a fluorescent dye like calcein or labelling with europium that becomes fluorescent when released Eu3+ binds to a chelator.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Fluorescence can be measured by means of multi-well fluorometers or by flow cytometry methods.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] There are also enzymatic-based assays in which the contents of the lysed cells includes cellular enzymes like GAPDH that remain active; supplying a substrate for that enzyme can catalyze a reaction whose product can be detected by luminescence or by absorbance.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] NK cells are involved in killing tumor cells and other cells that may lack MHC I on their surface, indicating a non-self cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] NK cells have been shown to behave similarly to memory cells due to their ability to react to destroy non-host cells only after interacting with a host cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] As NK cells are not themselves specific to certain pathways of immune control, they are utilized a majority of the time in ADCC as a less discriminate cell destroyer than antibody-specific apoptosis mechanisms.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] The ability of activated *ex vivo* NK cells has been a topic of interest for the treatment of tumors.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] After early clinical trials involving activation through cytokines produced poor results and severe toxicological side effects, more recent studies have produced success in regulating metastatic tumors using interleukin proteins to activate the NK cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] The effects against solid tumors of trastuzumab and rituximab monoclonal antibodies have been shown in experiments with mice to involve ADCC as an important mechanism of therapeutic action.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] In the clinic, the FcgRIII 158V/F polymorphism interfere with the ability to generate ADCC responses *in vitro* during trastuzumab treatment.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Multiple myeloma can be treated with daratumumab (Darzalex) monoclonal antibody.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Studies with *in vitro* materials and patient materials indicate that ADCC is an important mechanism, along with CDC (complement-dependent cytotoxicity).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] ADCC as used in immune control is typically more useful for viral infections than bacterial infections due to IgG antibodies binding to virus-related antigens over prokaryotic cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Instead of ADCC removing outside toxins, immunoglobulins neutralize products of infecting bacteria and encase infected host cells that have had bacterial toxins directly inserted through the cell membrane.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] ADCC is also important in the use of vaccines, as creation of antibodies and the destruction of antigens introduced to the host body are crucial to building immunity through small exposure to viral and bacterial proteins.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] Examples of this include vaccines targeting repeats in toxins (RTX) that are structurally crucial to a wide variety of erythrocyte-lysing bacteria, described as hemolysins.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-dependent-cellular-cytotoxicity] These bacteria target the CD18 portion of leukocytes, which has historically been shown to impact ADCC in adhesion-deficient cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Among treatment options for cancer, chemotherapy is most widely used.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Its main limitation is low target specificity.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Unlike chemotherapy, ADCs target tumor cells while sparing healthy cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] As of 2019, some 56 pharmaceutical companies were developing ADCs.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] ADCs combine the targeting properties of monoclonal antibodies with the cancer-killing capabilities of cytotoxic drugs, designed to discriminate between healthy and diseased tissue.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] An anticancer drug is coupled to an antibody that targets a specific tumor antigen (or protein) that, ideally, is only found in or on tumor cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] The biochemical reaction that occurs upon attaching triggers a signal in the tumor cell, which then absorbs, or internalizes, the antibody together with the linked cytotoxin.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] After the ADC is internalized, the cytotoxin kills the cancer.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Their targeting ability was believed to limit side effects for cancer patients and to give a wider therapeutic window than other chemotherapeutic agents, although this promise hasn't yet been realized in the clinic.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] ADC technologies have been featured in many publications, including scientific journals.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] The idea of drugs that would target tumor cells and ignore others was conceived in 1900 by German Nobel laureate Paul Ehrlich; he described the drugs as a "magic bullet" due to their targeting properties.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] In 2001 Pfizer/Wyeth's drug Gemtuzumab ozogamicin (brand name: Mylotarg) was approved based on a study with a surrogate endpoint, through the accelerated approval process.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] In June 2010, after evidence accumulated showing no evidence of benefit and significant toxicity, the U.S.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) forced the company to withdraw it.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Pfizer resubmitted it in 2017 based on a meta-analysis of prior trials and a new phase III trial.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] It was reintroduced into the US market in 2017.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Trastuzumab emtansine (ado-trastuzumab emtansine or T-DM1, brand name: Kadcyla, marketed by Genentech and Roche) was approved in February 2013 for the treatment of people with HER2-positive metastatic breast cancer (mBC) who had received prior treatment with trastuzumab and a taxane chemotherapy.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] The European Commission approved Inotuzumab ozogamicin as a monotherapy for the treatment of adults with relapsed or refractory CD22-positive B-cell precursor acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL) on June 30, 2017, under the brand name Besponsa (Pfizer/Wyeth), followed on August 17, 2017, by the FDA.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] In July 2018, Daiichi Sankyo Company, Limited and Glycotope GmbH have inked a pact regarding the combination of Glycotope's investigational tumor-associated TA-MUC1 antibody gatipotuzumab and Daiichi Sankyo's proprietary ADC technology for developing gatipotuzumab antibody drug conjugate.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] In 2019 AstraZeneca agreed to pay up to US$6.9 billion to jointly develop DS-8201 with Japan's Daiichi Sankyo.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] It is intended to replace Herceptin for treating breast cancer.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] DS8201 carries eight payloads, compared to the usual four.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Many of the payloads for oncology ADCs (oADC) are natural product based with some making covalent interactions with their target.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Payloads include the microtubulin inhibitors monomethyl auristatin E (MMAE), monomethyl auristatin F (MMAF) and mertansine, DNA binder calicheamicin and topoisomerase 1 inhibitors SN-38 and exatecan resulting in a renaissance for natural product total synthesis.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Glucocorticoid receptor modulators (GRMs) represent to most active payload class for iADCs.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Approaches releasing marketed GRM molecules such as dexamethasone and budesonide have been developed.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Modified GRM molecules have also been developed that enable the attachment of the linker with the term ADCidified describing the medicinal chemistry process of payload optimization to facilitate linker attachment.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Alternatives to small molecule payloads have also been investigated, for example, siRNA.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] More recently, targeted protein degraders have been explored as payloads for antibody conjugates.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] A 2025 study described a KIF11-directed degrader–antibody conjugate (DAC), in which a cereblon-recruiting degrader was used as the payload to induce antigen-dependent protein degradation and cytotoxicity in preclinical models.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] A stable link between the antibody and cytotoxic (anti-cancer) agent is a crucial aspect of an ADC.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] A stable ADC linker ensures that less of the cytotoxic payload falls off before reaching a tumor cell, improving safety, and limiting dosages.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Linkers are based on chemical motifs including disulfides, hydrazones or peptides (cleavable), or thioethers (noncleavable).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Cleavable and noncleavable linkers were proved to be safe in preclinical and clinical trials.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Brentuximab vedotin includes an enzyme-sensitive *cleavable linker* that delivers the antimicrotubule agent monomethyl auristatin E or MMAE, a synthetic antineoplastic agent, to human-specific CD30-positive malignant cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] MMAE inhibits cell division by blocking the polymerization of tubulin.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Because of its high toxicity MMAE cannot be used as a single-agent chemotherapeutic drug.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] However, MMAE linked to an anti-CD30 monoclonal antibody (cAC10, a cell membrane protein of the tumor necrosis factor or TNF receptor) was stable in extracellular fluid.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] It is cleavable by cathepsin and safe for therapy.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Trastuzumab emtansine is a combination of the microtubule-formation inhibitor mertansine (DM-1) and antibody trastuzumab that employs a stable, *non-cleavable linker*.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] The availability of better and more stable linkers has changed the function of the chemical bond.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] The type of linker, *cleavable* or *noncleavable*, lends specific properties to the cytotoxic drug.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] For example, a *non-cleavable* linker keeps the drug within the cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] As a result, the entire antibody, linker and cytotoxic (anti-cancer) agent enter the targeted cancer cell where the antibody is degraded into an amino acid.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] The resulting complex – amino acid, linker and cytotoxic agent – is considered to be the active drug.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] In contrast, *cleavable linkers* are detached by enzymes in the cancer cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] The cytotoxic payload can then escape from the targeted cell and, in a process called "bystander killing", attack neighboring cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Another type of cleavable linker, currently in development, adds an extra molecule between the cytotoxin and the cleavage site.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] This allows researchers to create ADCs with more flexibility without changing cleavage kinetics.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Researchers are developing a new method of peptide cleavage based on Edman degradation, a method of sequencing amino acids in a peptide.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Also under development are site-specific conjugation (TDCs) and novel conjugation techniques to further improve stability and therapeutic index, α emitting immunoconjugates, antibody-conjugated nanoparticles and antibody-oligonucleotide conjugates.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] As the antibody–drug conjugate field has matured, a more accurate definition of ADC is now Anything-Drug Conjugate.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Alternatives for the antibody targeting component now include multiple smaller antibody fragments like diabodies, Fab, scFv, and bicyclic peptides.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] The first generation uses linking technologies that conjugate drugs non-selectively to cysteine or lysine residues in the antibody, resulting in a heterogeneous mixture.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] This approach leads to suboptimal safety and efficacy and complicates optimization of the biological, physical and pharmacological properties.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Site-specific incorporation of unnatural amino acids generates a site for controlled and stable attachment.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] This enables the production of homogeneous ADCs with the antibody precisely linked to the drug and controlled ratios of antibody to drug, allowing the selection of a best-in-class ADC.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] An *Escherichia coli*-based open cell-free synthesis (OCFS) allows the synthesis of proteins containing site-specifically incorporated non-natural amino acids and has been optimized for predictable high-yield protein synthesis and folding.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] The absence of a cell wall allows the addition of non-natural factors to the system to manipulate transcription, translation and folding to provide precise protein expression modulation.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] Another strategy for site-specific amine conjugation to proteins is to replace lysine residues with arginine residues (LDVs).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] If all lysines are depleted then the only remaining free amine is at the amino terminus (N-terminus) of the protein.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] In the case where the protein is an antibody Fc domain, a recombinant LDV Fc can still be purified using protein A.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] LDV Fc proteins fused with short peptide targeting sequences can be used to deliver conjugated payloads, including nanoparticles, to specific cell surface proteins.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] The majority of ADCs under development or in clinical trials are for oncological and hematological indications.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] This is primarily driven by the inventory of monoclonal antibodies, which target various types of cancer.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/antibody-drug-conjugate] However, some developers are looking to expand the application to other important disease areas.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] An **epitope**, also known as **antigenic determinant**, is the part of an antigen that is recognized by the immune system, specifically by antibodies, B cells, or T cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] The part of an antibody that binds to the epitope is called a paratope.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Although epitopes are usually non-self proteins, sequences derived from the host that can be recognized (as in the case of autoimmune diseases) are also epitopes.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] The epitopes of protein antigens are divided into two categories, conformational epitopes and linear epitopes, based on their structure and interaction with the paratope.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Conformational and linear epitopes interact with the paratope based on the 3-D conformation adopted by the epitope, which is determined by the surface features of the involved epitope residues and the shape or tertiary structure of other segments of the antigen.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] A conformational epitope is formed by the 3-D conformation adopted by the interaction of discontiguous amino acid residues.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] In contrast, a linear epitope is formed by the 3-D conformation adopted by the interaction of contiguous amino acid residues.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] A linear epitope is not determined solely by the primary structure of the involved amino acids.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Residues that flank such amino acid residues, as well as more distant amino acid residues of the antigen affect the ability of the primary structure residues to adopt the epitope's 3-D conformation.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] T cell epitopes are presented on the surface of an antigen-presenting cell, where they are bound to major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] In humans, professional antigen-presenting cells are specialized to present MHC class II peptides, whereas most nucleated somatic cells present MHC class I peptides.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] T cell epitopes presented by MHC class I molecules are typically peptides between 8 and 11 amino acids in length, whereas MHC class II molecules present longer peptides, 13–17 amino acids in length, and non-classical MHC molecules also present non-peptidic epitopes such as glycolipids.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] The part of the antigen that immunoglobulin or antibodies bind to is called a B-cell epitope.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] B cell epitopes can be divided into two groups: conformational or linear.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] B cell epitopes are mainly conformational.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] There are additional epitope types when the quaternary structure is considered.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Epitopes that are masked when protein subunits aggregate are called cryptotopes.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Neotopes are epitopes that are only recognized while in a specific quaternary structure and the residues of the epitope can span multiple protein subunits.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Neotopes are not recognized once the subunits dissociate.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] This property is exploited by the immune system in regulation by anti-idiotypic antibodies (originally proposed by Nobel laureate Niels Kaj Jerne).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] If an antibody binds to an antigen's epitope, the paratope could become the epitope for another antibody that will then bind to it.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] If this second antibody is of IgM class, its binding can upregulate the immune response; if the second antibody is of IgG class, its binding can downregulate the immune response.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] MHC class I and II epitopes can be reliably predicted by computational means alone, although not all in-silico T cell epitope prediction algorithms are equivalent in their accuracy.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] There are two main methods of predicting peptide-MHC binding: data-driven and structure-based.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Structure based methods model the peptide-MHC structure and require great computational power.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Data-driven methods have higher predictive performance than structure-based methods.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Data-driven methods predict peptide-MHC binding based on peptide sequences that bind MHC molecules.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] By identifying T-cell epitopes, scientists can track, phenotype, and stimulate T-cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] There are two main methods of epitope mapping: either structural or functional studies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Methods for structurally mapping epitopes include X-ray crystallography, nuclear magnetic resonance, and electron microscopy.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] X-ray crystallography of Ag-Ab complexes is considered an accurate way to structurally map epitopes.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Nuclear magnetic resonance can be used to map epitopes by using data about the Ag-Ab complex.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] This method does not require crystal formation but can only work on small peptides and proteins.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Electron microscopy is a low-resolution method that can localize epitopes on larger antigens like virus particles.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Methods for functionally mapping epitopes often use binding assays such as western blot, dot blot, and/or ELISA to determine antibody binding.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Competition methods look to determine if two monoclonal antibodies (mABs) can bind to an antigen at the same time or compete with each other to bind at the same site.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Another technique involves high-throughput mutagenesis, an epitope mapping strategy developed to improve rapid mapping of conformational epitopes on structurally complex proteins.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Mutagenesis uses randomly/site-directed mutations at individual residues to map epitopes.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] B-cell epitope mapping can be used for the development of antibody therapeutics, peptide-based vaccines, and immunodiagnostic tools.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Epitopes are often used in proteomics and the study of other gene products.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Using recombinant DNA techniques genetic sequences coding for epitopes that are recognized by common antibodies can be fused to the gene.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Following synthesis, the resulting epitope tag allows the antibody to find the protein or other gene product enabling lab techniques for localisation, purification, and further molecular characterization including identifying the protein's binding partners.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Common epitopes used for this purpose are Myc-tag, HA-tag, FLAG-tag, GST-tag, 6xHis, V5-tag and OLLAS.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] An epitope tag was first described by Munro and Pelham to detect and track proteins in 1984 .
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Tags were quickly adapted for purifying proteins and to detect, pull down, and clone interaction partners of proteins .
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] These tags were originally referred to as "peptide tag", "epitope insertion", "marker sequence", and "epitope addition" , until "epitope tag" was coined and popularized.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Peptides can also be bound by proteins that form covalent bonds to the peptide, allowing irreversible immobilisation.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] These strategies have also been successfully applied to the development of "epitope-focused" vaccine design.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] The first epitope-based vaccine was developed in 1985 by Chaim Jacob and colleagues from The Weizmann Institute of Science.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Epitope-based vaccines stimulate humoral and cellular immune responses using isolated B-cell or T-cell epitopes.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] These vaccines can use multiple epitopes to increase their efficacy.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] To find epitopes to use for the vaccine, in silico mapping is often used.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Once candidate epitopes are found, the constructs are engineered and tested for vaccine efficiency.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] While epitope-based vaccines are generally safe, one possible side effect is cytokine storms.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] A **neoantigenic determinant** is an epitope on a neoantigen, which is a newly formed antigen that has not been previously recognized by the immune system.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Neoantigens are often associated with tumor antigens and are found in oncogenic cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Neoantigens and, by extension, neoantigenic determinants can be formed when a protein undergoes further modification within a biochemical pathway such as glycosylation, phosphorylation or proteolysis.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] This, by altering the structure of the protein, can produce new epitopes that are called neoantigenic determinants as they give rise to new antigenic determinants.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/epitope] Recognition requires separate, specific antibodies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] After forming hybridomas any non-hybrid cells are killed before screening and monoclonalization to create hybridoma lines that are derived from one parental cell and thus producing the same antibody against the desired target.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The production of monoclonal antibodies was invented by César Milstein and Georges J.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] They shared the Nobel Prize of 1984 for Medicine and Physiology with Niels Kaj Jerne, who made other contributions to immunology.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The term **hybridoma** was coined by Leonard Herzenberg during his sabbatical in Milstein's laboratory in 1976–1977.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Laboratory animals (mammals, e.g. mice) are first exposed to the antigen against which an antibody is to be generated.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Usually this is done by a series of injections of the antigen in question, over the course of several weeks.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] These injections are typically followed by the use of in vivo electroporation, which significantly enhances the immune response.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Once splenocytes are isolated from the mammal's spleen, the B cells are fused with immortalised myeloma cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The fusion of the B cells with myeloma cells can be done using electrofusion.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Electrofusion causes the B cells and myeloma cells to align and fuse with the application of an electric field.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Alternatively, the B-cells and myelomas can be made to fuse by chemical protocols, most often using polyethylene glycol.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The myeloma cells are selected beforehand to ensure they are not secreting antibody themselves and that they lack the hypoxanthine-guanine phosphoribosyltransferase (HGPRT) gene, making them sensitive (or vulnerable) to the HAT medium (see below).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Fused cells are incubated in HAT medium (hypoxanthine-aminopterin-thymidine medium) for roughly 10 to 14 days.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Aminopterin blocks the pathway that allows for nucleotide synthesis.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Hence, unfused myeloma cells die, as they cannot produce nucleotides by the *de novo* or salvage pathways because they lack HGPRT.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Removal of the unfused myeloma cells is necessary because they have the potential to outgrow other cells, especially weakly established hybridomas.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Unfused B cells die as they have a short life span.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] In this way, only the B cell-myeloma hybrids survive, since the HGPRT gene coming from the B cells is functional.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] These cells produce antibodies (a property of B cells) and are immortal (a property of myeloma cells).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The incubated medium is then diluted into multi-well plates to such an extent that each well contains only one cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Since the antibodies in a well are produced by the same B cell, they will be directed towards the same epitope, and are thus monoclonal antibodies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The next stage is a rapid primary screening process, which identifies and selects only those hybridomas that produce antibodies of appropriate specificity.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The first screening technique used is called ELISA.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The hybridoma culture supernatant, secondary enzyme labeled conjugate, and chromogenic substrate, are then incubated, and the formation of a colored product indicates a positive hybridoma.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Alternatively, immunocytochemical, western blot, and immunoprecipitation-mass spectrometry.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Unlike western blot assays, immunoprecipitation-mass spectrometry facilitates screening and ranking of clones which bind to the native (non-denaturated) forms of antigen proteins.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Flow cytometry screening has been used for primary screening of a large number (~1000) of hybridoma clones recognizing the native form of the antigen on the cell surface.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] In the flow cytometry-based screening, a mixture of antigen-negative cells and antigen-positive cells is used as the antigen to be tested for each hybridoma supernatant sample.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The B cell that produces the desired antibodies can be cloned to produce many identical daughter clones.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Supplemental media containing interleukin-6 (such as briclone) are essential for this step.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Once a hybridoma colony is established, it will continually grow in culture medium like RPMI-1640 (with antibiotics and fetal bovine serum) and produce antibodies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Multiwell plates are used initially to grow the hybridomas, and after selection, are changed to larger tissue culture flasks.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] This maintains the well-being of the hybridomas and provides enough cells for cryopreservation and supernatant for subsequent investigations.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The culture supernatant can yield 1 to 60 μg/ml of monoclonal antibody, which is maintained at -20 °C or lower until required.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] By using culture supernatant or a purified immunoglobulin preparation, further analysis of a potential monoclonal antibody producing hybridoma can be made in terms of reactivity, specificity, and cross-reactivity.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The use of monoclonal antibodies is numerous and includes the prevention, diagnosis, and treatment of disease.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] For example, monoclonal antibodies can distinguish subsets of B cells and T cells, which is helpful in identifying different types of leukaemias.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] In addition, specific monoclonal antibodies have been used to define cell surface markers on white blood cells and other cell types.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] This led to the cluster of differentiation series of markers.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] These are often referred to as CD markers and define several hundred different cell surface components of cells, each specified by binding of a particular monoclonal antibody.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Such antibodies are extremely useful for fluorescence-activated cell sorting, the specific isolation of particular types of cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] With the help of monoclonal antibodies, tissues and organs can be classified based on their expression of certain defined markers, which reflect tissue or cellular genesis.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Prostate specific antigen, placental alkaline phosphatase, human chorionic gonadotrophin, α-fetoprotein and others are organ-associated antigens and the production of monoclonal antibodies against these antigens helps in determining the nature of a primary tumor.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Monoclonal antibodies are especially useful in distinguishing morphologically similar lesions, like pleural and peritoneal mesothelioma, adenocarcinoma, and in the determination of the organ or tissue origin of undifferentiated metastases.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Selected monoclonal antibodies help in the detection of occult metastases (cancer of unknown primary origin) by immuno-cytological analysis of bone marrow, other tissue aspirates, as well as lymph nodes and other tissues and can have increased sensitivity over normal histopathological staining.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] One study performed a sensitive immuno-histochemical assay on bone marrow aspirates of 20 patients with localized prostate cancer.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Three monoclonal antibodies (T16, C26, and AE-1), capable of recognizing membrane and cytoskeletal antigens expressed by epithelial cells to detect tumour cells, were used in the assay.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Bone marrow aspirates of 22% of patients with localized prostate cancer (stage B, 0/5; Stage C, 2/4), and 36% patients with metastatic prostate cancer (Stage D1, 0/7 patients; Stage D2, 4/4 patients) had antigen-positive cells in their bone marrow.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] It was concluded that immuno-histochemical staining of bone marrow aspirates are very useful to detect occult bone marrow metastases in patients with apparently localized prostate cancer.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Although immuno-cytochemistry using tumor-associated monoclonal antibodies has led to an improved ability to detect occult breast cancer cells in bone marrow aspirates and peripheral blood, further development of this method is necessary before it can be used routinely.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] One major drawback of immuno-cytochemistry is that only tumor-associated and not tumor-specific monoclonal antibodies are used, and as a result, some cross-reaction with normal cells can occur.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] In order to effectively stage breast cancer and assess the efficacy of purging regimens prior to autologous stem cell infusion, it is important to detect even small quantities of breast cancer cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Immuno-histochemical methods are ideal for this purpose because they are simple, sensitive, and quite specific.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Franklin et al. performed a sensitive immuno-cytochemical assay by using a combination of four monoclonal antibodies (260F9, 520C9, 317G5 and BrE-3) against tumor cell surface glycoproteins to identify breast tumour cells in bone marrow and peripheral blood.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] They concluded from the results that immuno-cytochemical staining of bone marrow and peripheral blood is a sensitive and simple way to detect and quantify breast cancer cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] One of the main reasons for metastatic relapse in patients with solid tumours is the early dissemination of malignant cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The use of monoclonal antibodies (mAbs) specific for cytokeratins can identify disseminated individual epithelial tumor cells in the bone marrow.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] One study reports on having developed an immuno-cytochemical procedure for simultaneous labeling of cytokeratin component no.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] 18 (CK18) and prostate specific antigen (PSA).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] This would help in the further characterization of disseminated individual epithelial tumor cells in patients with prostate cancer.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The twelve control aspirates from patients with benign prostatic hyperplasia showed negative staining, which further supports the specificity of CK18 in detecting epithelial tumour cells in bone marrow.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] In most cases of malignant disease complicated by effusion, neoplastic cells can be easily recognized.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] However, in some cases, malignant cells are not so easily seen or their presence is too doubtful to call it a positive report.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The use of immuno-cytochemical techniques increases diagnostic accuracy in these cases.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Ghosh, Mason and Spriggs analysed 53 samples of pleural or peritoneal fluid from 41 patients with malignant disease.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Conventional cytological examination had not revealed any neoplastic cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Three monoclonal antibodies (anti-CEA, Ca 1 and HMFG-2) were used to search for malignant cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Immunocytochemical labelling was performed on unstained smears, which had been stored at -20 °C up to 18 months.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Twelve of the forty-one cases in which immuno-cytochemical staining was performed, revealed malignant cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The result represented an increase in diagnostic accuracy of approximately 20%.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] The study concluded that in patients with suspected malignant disease, immuno-cytochemical labeling should be used routinely in the examination of cytologically negative samples and has important implications with respect to patient management.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Another application of immuno-cytochemical staining is for the detection of two antigens in the same smear.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Double staining with light chain antibodies and with T and B cell markers can indicate the neoplastic origin of a lymphoma.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] One study has reported the isolation of a hybridoma cell line (clone 1E10), which produces a monoclonal antibody (IgM, k isotype).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] This monoclonal antibody shows specific immuno-cytochemical staining of nucleoli.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Tissues and tumours can be classified based on their expression of certain markers, with the help of monoclonal antibodies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] They help in distinguishing morphologically similar lesions and in determining the organ or tissue origin of undifferentiated metastases.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Immuno-cytological analysis of bone marrow, tissue aspirates, lymph nodes etc. with selected monoclonal antibodies help in the detection of occult metastases.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Monoclonal antibodies increase the sensitivity in detecting even small quantities of invasive or metastatic cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/hybridoma-technology] Monoclonal antibodies (mAbs) specific for cytokeratins can detect disseminated individual epithelial tumour cells in the bone marrow.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Antibodies are major components of humoral immunity.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] IgG is the main type of antibody found in blood and extracellular fluid, allowing it to control infection of body tissues.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] By binding many kinds of pathogens such as viruses, bacteria, and fungi, IgG protects the body from infection.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] IgG antibodies are generated following class switching and maturation of the antibody response, thus they participate predominantly in the secondary immune response.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] IgG is secreted as a monomer, which is small in size, allowing it to easily diffuse into tissues.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] It is the only antibody isotype that has receptors to facilitate passage through the human placenta, thereby providing protection to the fetus *in utero*.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Along with IgA secreted in the breast milk, residual IgG absorbed through the placenta provides the neonate with humoral immunity before its own immune system develops.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Colostrum contains a high percentage of IgG, especially bovine colostrum.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] In individuals with prior immunity to a pathogen, IgG appears about 24–48 hours after antigenic stimulation.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Therefore, in the first six months of life, the newborn has the same antibodies as the mother and can defend itself against all the pathogens the mother encountered in her life (even if only through vaccination) until these antibodies are degraded.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] This repertoire of immunoglobulins is crucial for newborns, who are very sensitive to infections, especially in the respiratory and digestive systems.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] IgG is also involved in regulating allergic reactions.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] According to Finkelman, there are two pathways of systemic anaphylaxis: antigens can cause systemic anaphylaxis in mice through classic pathway by cross-linking IgE bound to the mast cell receptor FcεRI, stimulating the release of both histamine and platelet activating factor (PAF).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] In the alternative pathway, antigens form complexes with IgG, which then cross-link the macrophage receptor FcγRIII, stimulating only PAF release.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] IgG antibodies can prevent IgE-mediated anaphylaxis by intercepting a specific antigen before it binds to mast cell–associated IgE.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Consequently, IgG antibodies block systemic anaphylaxis induced by small amounts of antigen, but can mediate systemic anaphylaxis induced by larger amounts.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] IgG antibodies are large globular proteins made of four peptide chains; two identical γ (gamma) heavy chains of about 50 kDa and two identical light chains of about 25 kDa.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] The resulting tetrameric quaternary structure, therefore, has a total molecular weight of about 150 kDa.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] The two heavy chains are linked to each other and to a light chain each by disulfide bonds.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] The resulting tetramer has two identical halves, which together form a Y-like shape.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Each end of the fork contains an identical antigen binding site.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] The Fc regions of IgGs bear a highly conserved N-glycosylation site at asparagine 297 in the constant region of the heavy chain.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] The N-glycans attached to this site are predominantly core-fucosylated biantennary structures of the complex type.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] In addition, small amounts of these N-glycans also bear bisecting GlcNAc and α-2,6-linked sialic acid residues.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] The N-glycan composition in IgG has been linked to several autoimmune, infectious and metabolic diseases.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] There are four IgG subclasses (IgG1, 2, 3, and 4) in humans, named in order of their abundance in serum (IgG1 being the most abundant).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Note: IgG affinity to Fc receptors on phagocytic cells is specific to individual species from which the antibody comes as well as the class.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] The structure of the hinge regions (region 6 in the diagram) contributes to the unique biological properties of each of the four IgG classes.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Even though there is about 95% similarity between their Fc regions, the structure of the hinge regions is relatively different.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] In 2013, the Temporal Model of human IgE and IgG function was proposed.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] This model suggests that IgG3 (and IgE) appear early in a response.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] The IgG3, though of relatively low affinity, allows IgG-mediated defences to join IgM-mediated defences in clearing foreign antigens.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Subsequently, higher affinity IgG1 and IgG2 are produced.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] The relative balance of these subclasses, in any immune complexes that form, helps determine the strength of the inflammatory processes that follow.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Finally, if antigen persists, high affinity IgG4 is produced, which dampens down inflammation by helping to curtail FcR-mediated processes.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] The relative ability of different IgG subclasses to fix complement may explain why some anti-donor antibody responses do harm a graft after organ transplantation.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] In a mouse model of autoantibody mediated anemia using IgG isotype switch variants of an anti erythrocytes autoantibody, it was found that mouse IgG2a was superior to IgG1 in activating complement.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Moreover, it was found that the IgG2a isotype was able to interact very efficiently with FcgammaR.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] As a result, 20 times higher doses of IgG1, in relationship to IgG2a autoantibodies, were required to induce autoantibody mediated pathology.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Since mouse IgG1 and human IgG1 are not entirely similar in function, and the inference of human antibody function from mouse studies must be done with great care.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] However, both human and mouse antibodies have different abilities to fix complement and to bind to Fc receptors.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] The measurement of immunoglobulin G can be a diagnostic tool for certain conditions, such as autoimmune hepatitis, if indicated by certain symptoms.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Clinically, measured IgG antibody levels are generally considered to be indicative of an individual's immune status to particular pathogens.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] A common example of this practice is titers drawn to demonstrate serologic immunity to measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR), hepatitis B virus, and varicella (chickenpox), among others.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/immunoglobulin-g] Testing of IgG is not indicated for diagnosis of allergy, and there is no evidence that it has any relationship to food intolerances.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] A **monoclonal antibody** (**mAb**, more rarely called **moAb**) is an antibody produced from a cell lineage made by cloning a unique white blood cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] All subsequent antibodies derived this way trace back to a unique parent cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Monoclonal antibodies are identical and can thus have monovalent affinity, binding only to a particular epitope (the part of an antigen that is recognized by the antibody).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In contrast, polyclonal antibodies are mixtures of antibodies derived from multiple plasma cell lineages which each bind to their particular target epitope.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Artificial antibodies known as bispecific monoclonal antibodies can also be engineered which include two different antigen binding sites (FABs) on the same antibody.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] It is possible to produce monoclonal antibodies that specifically bind to almost any suitable substance; they can then serve to detect or purify it.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] This capability has become an investigative tool in biochemistry, molecular biology, and medicine.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Monoclonal antibodies are used in the diagnosis of illnesses such as cancer and infections and are used therapeutically in the treatment of e.g. cancer and inflammatory diseases.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In the early 1900s, immunologist Paul Ehrlich proposed the idea of a *Zauberkugel* – "magic bullet", conceived of as a compound which selectively targeted a disease-causing organism, and could deliver a toxin for that organism.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] This underpinned the concept of monoclonal antibodies and monoclonal drug conjugates.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Ehrlich and Élie Metchnikoff received the 1908 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine for providing the theoretical basis for immunology.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] By the 1970s, lymphocytes producing a single antibody were known, in the form of multiple myeloma – a cancer affecting B-cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] These abnormal antibodies or paraproteins were used to study the structure of antibodies, but it was not yet possible to produce identical antibodies specific to a given antigen.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In 1973, Jerrold Schwaber described the production of monoclonal antibodies using human–mouse hybrid cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] This work remains widely cited among those using human-derived hybridomas.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In 1975, Georges Köhler and César Milstein succeeded in making fusions of myeloma cell lines with B cells to create hybridomas that could produce antibodies, specific to known antigens and that were immortalized.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] They and Niels Kaj Jerne shared the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1984 for the discovery.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In 1988, Gregory Winter and his team pioneered the techniques to humanize monoclonal antibodies, eliminating the reactions that many monoclonal antibodies caused in some patients.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] By the 1990s research was making progress in using monoclonal antibodies therapeutically, and in 2018, James P.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Allison and Tasuku Honjo received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discovery of cancer therapy by inhibition of negative immune regulation, using monoclonal antibodies that prevent inhibitory linkages.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The translational work needed to implement these ideas is credited to Lee Nadler.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] As explained in an NIH article, "He was the first to discover monoclonal antibodies directed against human B-cell–specific antigens and, in fact, all the known human B-cell–specific antigens were discovered in his laboratory.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Much of the work behind production of monoclonal antibodies is rooted in the production of hybridomas, which involves identifying antigen-specific plasma/plasmablast cells that produce antibodies specific to an antigen of interest and fusing these cells with myeloma cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Rabbit B-cells can be used to form a rabbit hybridoma.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Polyethylene glycol is used to fuse adjacent plasma membranes, but the success rate is low, so a selective medium in which only fused cells can grow is used.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] This is possible because myeloma cells have lost the ability to synthesize hypoxanthine-guanine-phosphoribosyl transferase (HGPRT), an enzyme necessary for the salvage synthesis of nucleic acids.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The absence of HGPRT is not a problem for these cells unless the de novo purine synthesis pathway is also disrupted.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Exposing cells to aminopterin (a folic acid analogue which inhibits dihydrofolate reductase) makes them unable to use the de novo pathway and become fully auxotrophic for nucleic acids, thus requiring supplementation to survive.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The selective culture medium is called HAT medium because it contains hypoxanthine, aminopterin and thymidine.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] This medium is selective for fused (hybridoma) cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Unfused myeloma cells cannot grow because they lack HGPRT and thus cannot replicate their DNA.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Unfused spleen cells cannot grow indefinitely because of their limited life span.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Only fused hybrid cells referred to as hybridomas, are able to grow indefinitely in the medium because the spleen cell partner supplies HGPRT and the myeloma partner has traits that make it immortal (similar to a cancer cell).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] This mixture of cells is then diluted and clones are grown from single parent cells on microtitre wells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The antibodies secreted by the different clones are then assayed for their ability to bind to the antigen (with a test such as ELISA or antigen microarray assay) or immuno-dot blot.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The most productive and stable clone is then selected for future use.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The hybridomas can be grown indefinitely in a suitable cell culture medium.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] They can also be injected into mice (in the peritoneal cavity, surrounding the gut).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] There, they produce tumors secreting an antibody-rich fluid called ascites fluid.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The medium must be enriched during *in vitro* selection to further favour hybridoma growth.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] This can be achieved by the use of a layer of feeder fibrocyte cells or supplement medium such as briclone.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Culture-media conditioned by macrophages can be used.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Production in cell culture is usually preferred as the ascites technique is painful to the animal.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Where alternate techniques exist, ascites is considered unethical.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Several monoclonal antibody technologies have been developed recently, such as phage display, single B cell culture, single cell amplification from various B cell populations and single plasma cell interrogation technologies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Different from traditional hybridoma technology, the newer technologies use molecular biology techniques to amplify the heavy and light chains of the antibody genes by PCR and produce in either bacterial or mammalian systems with recombinant technology.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] One of the advantages of the new technologies is applicable to multiple animals, such as rabbit, llama, chicken and other common experimental animals in the laboratory.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] After obtaining either a media sample of cultured hybridomas or a sample of ascites fluid, the desired antibodies must be extracted.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Cell culture sample contaminants consist primarily of media components such as growth factors, hormones and transferrins.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In contrast, the *in vivo* sample is likely to have host antibodies, proteases, nucleases, nucleic acids and viruses.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In both cases, other secretions by the hybridomas such as cytokines may be present.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] There may also be bacterial contamination and, as a result, endotoxins that are secreted by the bacteria.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Depending on the complexity of the media required in cell culture and thus the contaminants, one or the other method (*in vivo* or *in vitro*) may be preferable.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The sample is first conditioned, or prepared for purification.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Cells, cell debris, lipids, and clotted material are first removed, typically by centrifugation followed by filtration with a 0.45 μm filter.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] These large particles can cause a phenomenon called membrane fouling in later purification steps.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In addition, the concentration of product in the sample may not be sufficient, especially in cases where the desired antibody is produced by a low-secreting cell line.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The sample is therefore concentrated by ultrafiltration or dialysis.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Most of the charged impurities are usually anions such as nucleic acids and endotoxins.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] These can be separated by ion exchange chromatography.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Either cation exchange chromatography is used at a low enough pH that the desired antibody binds to the column while anions flow through, or anion exchange chromatography is used at a high enough pH that the desired antibody flows through the column while anions bind to it.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Various proteins can also be separated along with the anions based on their isoelectric point (pI).
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In proteins, the isoelectric point (pI) is defined as the pH at which a protein has no net charge.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] When the pH > pI, a protein has a net negative charge, and when the pH < pI, a protein has a net positive charge.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] For example, albumin has a pI of 4.8, which is significantly lower than that of most monoclonal antibodies, which have a pI of 6.1.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Thus, at a pH between 4.8 and 6.1, the average charge of albumin molecules is likely to be more negative, while mAbs molecules are positively charged and hence it is possible to separate them.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Transferrin, on the other hand, has a pI of 5.9, so it cannot be easily separated by this method.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] A difference in pI of at least 1 is necessary for a good separation.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Transferrin can instead be removed by size exclusion chromatography.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] This method is one of the more reliable chromatography techniques.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Since we are dealing with proteins, properties such as charge and affinity are not consistent and vary with pH as molecules are protonated and deprotonated, while size stays relatively constant.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Nonetheless, it has drawbacks such as low resolution, low capacity and low elution times.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] A much quicker, single-step method of separation is protein A/G affinity chromatography.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The antibody selectively binds to protein A/G, so a high level of purity (generally >80%) is obtained.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The generally harsh conditions of this method may damage easily damaged antibodies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] A low pH can break the bonds to remove the antibody from the column.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In addition to possibly affecting the product, low pH can cause protein A/G itself to leak off the column and appear in the eluted sample.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Gentle elution buffer systems that employ high salt concentrations are available to avoid exposing sensitive antibodies to low pH.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Cost is also an important consideration with this method because immobilized protein A/G is a more expensive resin.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] To achieve maximum purity in a single step, affinity purification can be performed, using the antigen to provide specificity for the antibody.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In this method, the antigen used to generate the antibody is covalently attached to an agarose support.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] If the antigen is a peptide, it is commonly synthesized with a terminal cysteine, which allows selective attachment to a carrier protein, such as KLH during development and to support purification.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The antibody-containing medium is then incubated with the immobilized antigen, either in batch or as the antibody is passed through a column, where it selectively binds and can be retained while impurities are washed away.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] An elution with a low pH buffer or a more gentle, high salt elution buffer is then used to recover purified antibody from the support.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Product heterogeneity is common in monoclonal antibodies and other recombinant biological products and is typically introduced either upstream during expression or downstream during manufacturing.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] These variants are typically aggregates, deamidation products, glycosylation variants, oxidized amino acid side chains, as well as amino and carboxyl terminal amino acid additions.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] These seemingly minute structural changes can affect preclinical stability and process optimization as well as therapeutic product potency, bioavailability and immunogenicity.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The generally accepted purification method of process streams for monoclonal antibodies includes capture of the product target with protein A, elution, acidification to inactivate potential mammalian viruses, followed by ion chromatography, first with anion beads and then with cation beads.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Displacement chromatography has been used to identify and characterize these often unseen variants in quantities that are suitable for subsequent preclinical evaluation regimens such as animal pharmacokinetic studies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Knowledge gained during the preclinical development phase is critical for enhanced product quality understanding and provides a basis for risk management and increased regulatory flexibility.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The recent Food and Drug Administration's Quality by Design initiative attempts to provide guidance on development and to facilitate design of products and processes that maximizes efficacy and safety profile while enhancing product manufacturability.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The production of recombinant monoclonal antibodies involves repertoire cloning, CRISPR/Cas9, or phage display/yeast display technologies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Recombinant antibody engineering involves antibody production by the use of viruses or yeast, rather than mice.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] These techniques rely on rapid cloning of immunoglobulin gene segments to create libraries of antibodies with slightly different amino acid sequences from which antibodies with desired specificities can be selected.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The phage antibody libraries are a variant of phage antigen libraries.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] These techniques can be used to enhance the specificity with which antibodies recognize antigens, their stability in various environmental conditions, their therapeutic efficacy and their detectability in diagnostic applications.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Fermentation chambers have been used for large scale antibody production.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Recombinant DNA has been explored since the late 1980s to increase residence times.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In one approach called "CDR grafting", mouse DNA encoding the binding portion of a monoclonal antibody was merged with human antibody-producing DNA in living cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The expression of this "chimeric" or "humanised" DNA through cell culture yielded part-mouse, part-human antibodies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Ever since the discovery that monoclonal antibodies could be generated, scientists have targeted the creation of *fully* human products to reduce the side effects of humanised or chimeric antibodies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Several successful approaches have been proposed: transgenic mice, phage display and single B cell cloning.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Monoclonal antibodies are more expensive to manufacture than small molecules due to the complex processes involved and the general size of the molecules, all in addition to the enormous research and development costs involved in bringing a new chemical entity to patients.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] They are priced to enable manufacturers to recoup the typically large investment costs, and where there are no price controls, such as the United States, prices can be higher if they provide great value.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Once monoclonal antibodies for a given substance have been produced, they can be used to detect the presence of this substance.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Proteins can be detected using the Western blot and immuno dot blot tests.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In immunohistochemistry, monoclonal antibodies can be used to detect antigens in fixed tissue sections, and similarly, immunofluorescence can be used to detect a substance in either frozen tissue section or live cells.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Antibodies can also be used to purify their target compounds from mixtures, using the method of immunoprecipitation.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Therapeutic monoclonal antibodies act through multiple mechanisms, such as blocking of targeted molecule functions, inducing apoptosis in cells which express the target, or by modulating signalling pathways.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] One possible treatment for cancer involves monoclonal antibodies that bind only to cancer-cell-specific antigens and induce an immune response against the target cancer cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Such mAbs can be modified for delivery of a toxin, radioisotope, cytokine or other active conjugate or to design bispecific antibodies that can bind with their Fab regions both to target antigen and to a conjugate or effector cell.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Every intact antibody can bind to cell receptors or other proteins with its Fc region.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Monoclonal antibodies used for autoimmune diseases include infliximab and adalimumab, which are effective in rheumatoid arthritis, Crohn's disease, ulcerative colitis and ankylosing spondylitis by their ability to bind to and inhibit TNF-α.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Basiliximab and daclizumab inhibit IL-2 on activated T cells and thereby help prevent acute rejection of kidney transplants.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Omalizumab inhibits human immunoglobulin E (IgE) and is useful in treating moderate-to-severe allergic asthma.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Monoclonal antibodies for research applications can be found directly from antibody suppliers, or through use of a specialist search engine like CiteAb.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Below are examples of clinically important monoclonal antibodies.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In 2020, the monoclonal antibody therapies bamlanivimab/etesevimab and casirivimab/imdevimab were given emergency use authorizations by the US Food and Drug Administration to reduce the number of hospitalizations, emergency room visits, and deaths because of COVID-19.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In September 2021, the Biden administration purchased US$2.9 billion worth of Regeneron monoclonal antibodies at $2,100 per dose to curb the shortage.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] As of December 2021, *in vitro* neutralization tests indicate monoclonal antibody therapies (with the exception of sotrovimab and tixagevimab/cilgavimab) were not likely to be active against the Omicron variant.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Over 2021–22, two Cochrane reviews found insufficient evidence for using neutralizing monoclonal antibodies to treat COVID-19 infections.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] The reviews applied only to people who were unvaccinated against COVID‐19, and only to the COVID-19 variants existing during the studies, not to newer variants, such as Omicron.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] In March 2024, pemivibart, a monoclonal antibody drug, received an emergency use authorization from the US FDA for use as pre-exposure prophylaxis to protect certain moderately to severely immunocompromised individuals against COVID-19.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] Several monoclonal antibodies, such as bevacizumab and cetuximab, can cause different kinds of side effects.
[src:monoclonal-antibodies/monoclonal-antibody] These side effects can be categorized into common and serious side effects.
